---
import Base from "../../layouts/Base.astro";
---

<Base
  title="On Retainer · Ennea Evolution"
  description="Some companies don't want a workshop. They want somebody who knows them. On retainer, I become a standing part of how your company takes care of its people."
>
  <div style="--accent:#006073;">
    <!-- SECTION 1 · white · hero split -->
    <section class="panel">
      <div class="container split" style="align-items:center;">
        <div>
          <p class="eyebrow" style="--accent:var(--teal);">Professional Work</p>
          <h1>Some companies don't want a workshop. They want somebody who knows them.</h1>
          <p class="lead">On retainer, I become a standing part of how your company takes care of its people to get the work done.</p>
          <a href="/get-started" class="btn" style="margin-top:1rem;">Let's Talk</a>
        </div>
        <div class="photo-block" style="--block:#FCE9CD;">
          <div class="photo-slot" style="--tint:#ffffff;">
            <span>Photo coming soon</span>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <hr class="hairline-gold" />

    <!-- SECTION 2 · white · partnerships -->
    <section class="panel">
      <div class="container narrow">
        <h3>Partnerships</h3>
        <p>A workshop is a day. This is a relationship.</p>
        <p>On retainer, I'm not a vendor you book. I'm someone who knows your business, your people, and what you're trying to build, and who's around through the year instead of for an afternoon. Nobody has to be briefed. I already know what happened last quarter and who was in the room.</p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- SECTION 3 · white · what it can look like -->
    <section class="panel" style="padding-top:0;">
      <div class="container narrow">
        <h3>What it can look like</h3>
        <p>This is different at every company. Here's what it has actually looked like.</p>
        <p style="margin-top:1.75rem;"><strong>Quarterly workshops, planned with you.</strong> Every quarter we sit down, usually with you or whoever holds your people function, and work out what your company actually needs right now. What would help. What would fix something. What would be genuinely fun. Then I build it and run it. In between, there can be lunch and learns, where the ideas get used on what's really happening, instead of staying theoretical.</p>
        <p><strong>Confidential sessions your people can use.</strong> A set number of sessions a month that anyone in the company can sign up for. Someone managing a team that's gotten hard. Someone going through something at home that's showing up at work. Someone who needs to think out loud with a person who isn't their boss. Your people get somewhere to take it, and you stop being the only place it can go.</p>
        <p><strong>A voice inside your company.</strong> An Enneagram column or a communication corner in your newsletter, a few times a year. It's a small thing. It's also how the language stays alive between workshops, which is the difference between a team that learned something and a team that uses it.</p>
        <p><strong>Culture, built and then tended.</strong> Some companies want to build their culture on purpose rather than let it happen to them. We plan it, roll it out, and then keep after it, because culture doesn't hold on its own. Sometimes that's the planning only. Sometimes I stay and help you run it for years.</p>
        <p>Most companies mix these, and the mix changes as they do.</p>
        <div class="photo-block" style="--block:#FCE9CD; margin-top:2.5rem;">
          <div class="photo">
            <img src="/img/retainer-partners.jpg" alt="People talking over coffee at a relaxed outdoor gathering" width="1400" height="927" loading="lazy" />
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <hr class="hairline-gold" />

    <!-- SECTION 4 · white · who this tends to be for -->
    <section class="panel">
      <div class="container narrow">
        <h3>Who this tends to be for</h3>
        <p>One is an established company, successful for years, that can feel itself settling. Nothing is wrong. It's gotten comfortable, and comfortable is a slow leak. This is the thing that wakes it back up.</p>
        <p>The other is a younger company growing fast enough to know its culture is being set right now, whether anyone chooses it or not. They'd rather choose it.</p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- SECTION 5 · tint #FCE9CD · what you're actually getting -->
    <section class="panel tint-band" style="--tint:#FCE9CD;">
      <div class="container narrow">
        <h3>What you're actually getting</h3>
        <p>Most companies can't justify carrying someone full time with this skill set, and they shouldn't have to. On retainer you get the benefit without the salary.</p>
        <p>You also get the thing a consultant flying in for a day can't give you. Someone who knows your people by name, knows what you tried last spring and how it went, and can tell you when the answer is to "do nothing" for a quarter.</p>
        <blockquote class="pullquote" style="--accent:var(--teal);">By the end of a year, this isn't a workshop your company attended. It's how your company talks.</blockquote>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- SECTION 6 · white · a note about workplace support -->
    <section class="panel">
      <div class="container narrow">
        <p style="margin-bottom:0;">The confidential side of this has its own page, if that's the part you're here for. <a href="/professional-work/workplace-support">Workplace Support</a> covers mediation, facilitated conversations, and support for the situations a manager shouldn't have to carry alone. It can stand on its own or sit inside a retainer.</p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <hr class="hairline-gold" />

    <!-- SECTION 7 · white · let's talk it through -->
    <section class="panel center">
      <div class="container narrow">
        <h3>Let's talk it through</h3>
        <p>Tell me about your company and what you're trying to build. We'll work out what shape this should take, and I'll tell you honestly whether it's the right fit.</p>
        <a href="/get-started" class="btn" style="margin-top:0.5rem;">Let's Talk</a>
      </div>
    </section>
  </div>
</Base>
